# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anke-eymer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in recently united Germany on 2 December 1990 to elect the members of the 12th Bundestag, within the regular time of nearly four years after the January 1987 West German federal election.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] Due to the accession of the former East German states on 3 October, after which the Bundestag was expanded with East German Volkskammer delegates, the elections were the first democratic all-German elections since the early 1930s.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The result was a comprehensive victory for Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his governing coalition of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union and the Free Democratic Party (FDP), which was reelected to a third term (and a fourth in 1994).
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The *second vote* (preferred national party, *first vote* is for a local candidate) result of the CDU/CSU, 20,358,096 votes, remains the highest ever total vote count in a democratic German election.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The elections marked the first since 1957 that a party other than CDU/CSU and the Social Democratic Party (SPD) won a constituency seat (Direktmandat), breaking up the dominance of the two *Volksparteien*.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The first (and only) time since 1957 that FDP won a constituency seat was by Uwe Lühr in Halle, home of Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the "architect of German reunification".
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] In addition, Gregor Gysi (PDS) won Berlin-Marzahn – Hellersdorf.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] This was the first election conducted after German reunification which took place on 3 October.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] Previously, the Volkskammer had selected 144 of its members which were then co-opted as Members of the German Bundestag and served until the end of the 11th Bundestag.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] Almost 150 seats had been added to represent the re-established eastern states of Germany, without reducing the number of western members.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The euphoria following the reunification gave the ruling CDU/CSU–FDP coalition a dramatic advantage in both Western and Eastern Germany throughout the campaign.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] For this election only, the country was divided into two areas for the purposes of the five-percent threshold: the former West German states and West Berlin, and the former East German states and East Berlin.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] Second votes were counted separately in each area, and passing the threshold in either area was sufficient to enter the Bundestag and receive list seats.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] As a result, while the Western Greens (4.8% of western second votes) did not gain representation, their ideologically-similar Eastern Alliance 90 (6.2% of eastern second votes) did, with both merging to form Alliance 90/The Greens in 1993.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The Party of Democratic Socialism also entered the Bundestag with 11.1% of eastern second votes, despite receiving just 0.3% of the western second vote (and only 2.4% nationwide).
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] However, the distribution of seats to state lists was not divided in this manner and still calculated on the national level, which resulted in the PDS receiving a list seat (Ulla Jelpke) in the most populous state of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The German Social Union (DSU) under leader Hansjoachim Walther, a right-wing party modeled after the Bavarian CSU running only in former East Germany, failed to achieve the separate five percent hurdle, only receiving around 1% of the vote in the eastern states, mostly in the southeast.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] As part of the co-option, the DSU had previously had eight Members of the Bundestag, who sat as guests in the CDU/CSU caucus.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The CSU, which had heavily supported the DSU financially, severed its ties in 1993 and the party fell into irrelevancy.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] All change figures are relative to the Bundestag as it existed after the grant of full voting member status to West Berlin's delegation and co-optation of Volkskammer members to represent East Germany.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The governing CDU/CSU-FDP coalition was returned to office with a landslide majority, and Helmut Kohl remained chancellor.
[src:anke-eymer/1990-german-federal-election] The CDU did exceptionally well in the former East Germany, which had been the heartland of the SPD before the Nazi era.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:anke-eymer/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:anke-eymer/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Albert Dess graduated from Agricultural college in 1966.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He obtained his Master's in agriculture in 1979.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Albert had a Secondary occupation as farmer and worked in commerce and industry.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He became managing director of a farming cooperative and in 1977, a Full-time farmer/training establishment.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] In 1974 Albert Dess became the District Chairman of the Junge Union.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] In 1981 he became a Member of the CSU district executive and later in 1984, he became the Municipal Chairman of the CSU.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He later rose in ranks by becoming the District Chairman in 1987, Regional Vice-chairman (1989–1995) and Regional Chairman (1995) of the CSU Agricultural Association.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Albert was a Member of the CSU district executive from 1989 and in 1997, a member of the CSU Regional Executive Committee.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] From 1972 to 1996 he was in the Municipal Councillor, Berngau.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He became a District Councillor, Neumarkt/Oberpfalz in 1978.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] In 1984–1996, he was the Vice-chairman of Neumarkt/Oberpfalz district council and from 1984 to 1996, the Mayor of Berngau.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Albert Dess from 1992 to 2004 was the Farm policy spokesman for the CSU Regional Group in the Bundestag and from 1997 to 2004, a Member of the CDU/CSU Group Executive Committee.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He later became the Chairman of the CSU Regional Group working party for Agriculture, Consumer Protection, Environment, Transport, Building and Energy from 2000 to 2004.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Dess was a member of the European Parliament's Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development (AGRI).
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] He was a substitute for the Committee on International Trade (INTRA), a member of the delegation for relations with Mercosur and a substitute for the delegation to the ACP-EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] In May 2018, Dess announced that he would not stand in the 2019 European elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] Outside Germany, Dess is best known for trying to introduce in the European Parliament a Volkswagen-written piece of legislation that would have exempted a whole class of vehicle from pollution controls.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-dess] The proposal was dropped after the Volkswagen emissions violation scandal erupted and Dress has thus far refused requests to comment on his actions.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Probst was born in Garching bei München, Upper Bavaria.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] After graduation in 1951 from the Maximilians Gymnasium in Munich, Probst took an agricultural apprenticeship.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He then studied agricultural sciences at the Technical University of Munich, graduating in 1958 with a diploma as an agricultural engineer.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] In Munich, he served in the Catholic student group K.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He then joined the agricultural civil service, working at the milk research institute at TU Munich.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He left this institute in 1961, after completing research.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He returned to TU Munich in 1963, after two years as an agriculture adviser in France, to work on a research project concerning population genetics.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] At this time he began to participate in municipal politics.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Probst was deputy chair of the culture team of the Christian Socialist Union for many years.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] From 1960 to 1973 he belonged to the country of the circle day of the district of Munich.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He was also a member of the Garching local council from 1966 until 1990.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] From 1969 to 1998 Probst was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He was chair of the Committee on Development and Science from 1972 to 1976, and from 1976 to 1982 chaired the Committee on Research and Technology.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Until 1982, he chaired the science development team and served as spokesperson for the Christian Socialist Union rural group.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Probst was a directly selected delegate of the Munich/Freising constituency in the Bundestag.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] From 1991 to 1999 he represented Germany at parliamentary meetings of the Council of Europe, and at the European Union.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] On 4 October 1982 Probst became Parliamentary Secretary of State at the Federal Ministry for Research and Technology, in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Here he advocated the early provision of computers in schools.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] He served until the Bundestag election in 1990, leaving government on 24 January 1991.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-probst] Probst is married and has four children.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] Rupprecht first became a member of the Bundestag in the 2002 German federal election, representing the Weiden district.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] In parliament, he initially served as deputy chair of the Committee on Economic Affairs from 2005 to 2009.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] In 2009, he moved to the Committee for Education, Research and Technology Assessment.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] Also since 2009, he has been the CDU/CSU parliamentary group's spokesperson on education and research.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] From 2008 to 2010, Rupprecht chaired the parliamentary body providing oversight of the Special Financial Market Stabilization Funds (SoFFin).
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] In the negotiations to form a fourth coalition government under Chancellor Angela Merkel following the 2017 federal elections, Rupprecht was part of the working group on education policy, led by Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, Stefan Müller and Hubertus Heil.
[src:anke-eymer/albert-rupprecht] In June 2017, Rupprecht voted against Germany's introduction of same-sex marriage.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In 1992 and 1993 Bonde was an exchange student at Kahuku High School (Oahu, Hawaii, USA).
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] From 2002 to 2011, Bonde was a member of the Bundestag.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] There he represented his constituency *283 Emmendingen-Lahr*, a rural area in the Black Forest that covers 41 municipalities in the state of Baden-Württemberg.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] Bonde was first elected in 2002 and was reelected in 2005 and 2009.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] Bonde served on the Defense Committee and on the Budget Committee.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] He was also a member of the Financial Markets Committee that supervises the German banking rescue package.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] On the Budget Committee, Bonde served as “rapporteur-general” for agriculture (the equivalent to chairing a small subcommittee) as “rapporteur” (equivalent to being a member of a small subcommittee) for defence, economy and labor.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] From 2008 to 2010, Bonde was a member of the parliamentary body providing oversight of the Special Financial Market Stabilization Funds (SoFFin).
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In addition to his committee assignments, Bonde served as vice-chairman of the German-American Parliamentary Group and of the Aviation & Space Caucus of the German Bundestag.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In 2011, Bonde was appointed State Minister for Rural Areas, Agriculture and Consumer Rights in the state government of Baden-Württemberg under Minister-President Winfried Kretschmann.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In the negotiations to form a coalition government with the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) under the leadership of Kretschmann following the 2016 state elections, Bonde led his party’s delegation in the working group on rural affairs and consumer protection.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] On 12 May 2016 Peter Hauk (CDU) became his successor.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In December 2017, the board of trustees of the German Federal Environment Foundation (DBU) – at the time chaired by Rita Schwarzelühr-Sutter – appointed Bonde as the organization's secretary general.
[src:anke-eymer/alexander-bonde] In the negotiations to form another coalition government under Kretschmann's leadership following the 2021 state elections, Bonde was a member of the working group on climate, environmental policy and energy, co-chaired by Sandra Detzer and Andreas Jung.
[src:anke-eymer/anke-eymer] She was a member of the German Bundestag from 1990 to 2009.
[src:anke-eymer/anke-eymer] As a member of the German Bundestag, she was a member of the Committee on Women and Youth, the Committee on Family and Senior Citizens and later a member of the Committee on Foreign Affairs, rapporteur for international women's policy, international cultural policy and for sub-Saharan Africa.
